  "text": "For this purpose, we deployed the following procedure. First, for each dimension, we subtracted each corresponding template from its counterpart, thereby obtaining another template akin to a classification image (CI) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] -that is, a linear estimate of the image-based template that best accounts for identity-related scores along a given dimension (Methods). Then, this template was assessed pixel-by-pixel with respect to a randomly-generated distribution of templates (i.e., by permuting the scores associated with facial identities) in order to reveal pixel values lower or higher than chance (two-tailed permutation test; FDR correction across pixels, q<0.05). These analyses were performed separately for each color channel after converting images to CIEL*a*b* (where L*, a* and b* approximate the lightness, red:green and yellow:blue color-opponent channels of human vision). Examples of raw classification images and their analyses are shown in Fig.  2 .",
